## Architecture Diagram

```mermaid
graph LR
    UI["View<br/>(Login / SignUp)"]
    VM["AuthViewModel<br/>(ChangeNotifier)"]
    REPO["AuthRepository"]
    SVC["AuthService"]
    DIO["DioHelper"]
    API["REST API"]
    SP["SharedPreferences"]

    UI -->|watches| VM
    VM -->|calls| REPO
    REPO -->|calls| SVC
    SVC -->|uses| DIO
    DIO -->|HTTP| API
    REPO -->|reads/writes token| SP
    DIO -->|reads token on init| SP
```

---

## Best Practices Applied

| Principle | How it's applied |
|-----------|-----------------|
| **Separation of Concerns** | Service → raw HTTP · Repository → parsing + error + token · ViewModel → UI state · View → rendering |
| **DRY** | `_persistTokenAndReinitDio()` shared between login & signUp; `_reset()` in ViewModel |
| **Single Responsibility** | Each class has exactly one reason to change |
| **Dependency Inversion** | Repository depends on `AuthService` abstraction injected via constructor; resolved through GetIt |
| **Error Handling** | All errors flow through `ErrorHandler.handle()` → [AppException](file:///d:/Flutter_Projects/Cureta-Frontend/lib/core/error_handling/app_exceptions.dart#12-70) → ViewModel exposes typed [AppException](file:///d:/Flutter_Projects/Cureta-Frontend/lib/core/error_handling/app_exceptions.dart#12-70) → UI uses `ErrorHandler.show()` |
| **Testability** | Constructor injection makes mocking straightforward in unit tests |
